# Fluff Date: 2026-03-09 12:33:56
<overview>
<p>The Maxim Mk II Transport is a joint venture between Cyclops Incorporated and Scarborough Manufacturers, developed in the aftermath of the Jihad for the newly formed Republic of the Sphere's Armed Forces. Introduced in 3083, the Mk II was designed from the ground up as a dedicated battle armor carrier, prioritizing troop capacity and survivability over the heavy weaponry that defined its predecessor.</p><p>The design philosophy behind the Mk II serves as a deliberate departure from the original Maxim's role as a heavily armed combat transport. By minimizing the weapons suite, the Mk II encourages crews to withdraw from dangerous situations rather than engage, extending the vehicle's operational lifespan and reducing replacement costs for the cash-strapped Republic military.</p>
</overview>

<capabilities>
<p>The Mk II's spacious sixteen-ton infantry bay is its defining feature, capable of carrying a full platoon of battle armor or an entire company of conventional infantry. Adjustable handholds and equipment hooks line the walls, while storage bins offer space for ammunition, power packs, and other combat essentials. Multifunction fold-down stations accommodate both standard power armor and quad suits, with a quick release system for rapid egress.</p><p>A pair of Helga Series three-tube Multi-Missile Launchers provide the sole offensive armament, mounted in the turret. Though light by Maxim standards, the MML-3s offer tactical flexibility through their ability to fire standard LRM or SRM loads as well as specialty munitions like Thunder LRM mines. Two tons of ammunition stored in a CASE-protected bin ensure the crew and passengers survive any catastrophic detonation. Five and a half tons of ArcShield Heavy ferro-fibrous armor provide above-average protection for the weight class. The PowerTech 165 Highlifter fusion engine maintains the traditional Maxim top speed of 129 kilometers per hour while eliminating the logistical burden of fuel resupply. The primary drawback is the near total reliance on embarked troops for close defense once the infantry has deployed.</p>
</capabilities>

<deployment>
<p>The standard Mk II is produced at both the Cyclops facility on Skye and the Scarborough plant on Al Na'ir. Originally built exclusively for the Republic Armed Forces, the design has since entered service with successor states including the Draconis Combine, the Lyran Commonwealth, and Clan occupation forces. Approximately ninety percent of Mk II production is the standard configuration, reflecting the RAF's emphasis on maximizing battle armor transport capacity across its formations.</p>
</deployment>

<history>
<p>The Maxim Mk II emerged from the Republic Armed Forces' "Anyone Can Be a Hero" recruiting campaign, which dramatically expanded the need for heavy infantry carriers capable of deploying battle armor in large numbers. Both Cyclops Industries and Scarborough Manufacturers submitted competing proposals, each drawing on their decades of experience producing the original Maxim. When the RAF selected the Maxim as the basis for their new transport, neither company could independently meet the production requirements or the RAF's demanding specifications.</p><p>Scarborough approached Cyclops with a joint venture proposal, but the partnership proved contentious from the start. Heated debates erupted over the appropriate battlefield role for the Mk II. Amidst significant media coverage, Cyclops's executive VP of development, Shiloh Connolly, resigned over the direction of the project. Connolly publicly stated that the final specifications ignored the Maxim's lengthy and successful history of combat support roles, producing a vehicle designed to avoid fights rather than win them. Scarborough's engineers countered that reducing the weapons load would keep the Mk II out of combat and extend its service life, allowing the RAF to invest more in battle armor and other equipment. The RAF ultimately sided with Scarborough's philosophy, and the Maxim Mk II entered production in 3083.</p><p>The entire first production run went to the regiments of the Hastati Sentinels. Subsequent runs were divided between the Sentinels, Triarii Protectors, and Principes Guards, with approximately ninety percent being the standard configuration. The RAF standard procedure called for each Mk II to transport a full platoon of battle armor, though additional configurations could accommodate two motorized infantry platoons, four platoons of jump infantry, or five platoons of conventional foot soldiers. Multi-role loadouts typically included two squads of battle armor alongside two platoons of jump or foot infantry.</p><p>The Mk II Infantry Support variant, produced exclusively on Skye and known colloquially as the "Shiloh" after the departed Cyclops executive, addressed the concerns Connolly had raised. By halving the infantry bay and installing light PPCs and machine guns, the Shiloh provided substantially more organic firepower. The variant was exported to the Lyran Commonwealth, where it was assigned to units in the Bolan and Donegal provinces. Beginning in 3088, the RAF also deployed standard Mk IIs to prefecture militias, expanding the vehicle's presence throughout Republic territory.</p><p>Production at both the Skye and Al Na'ir facilities continued through the Republic era and into the Dark Age. When Clan Jade Falcon seized Skye, the Cyclops facility fell under Falcon control, though production of the Mk II continued for the new owners. Following the formation of the ilClan, the Skye plant transferred to Clan Wolf Empire authority. The Al Na'ir facility passed through Word of Blake control during the Jihad, then Republic of the Sphere governance, before returning to Draconis Combine ownership as the Republic contracted. Both plants remain active producers of the Mk II through the current era, ensuring the design continues to serve multiple successor states simultaneously.</p><p>The ECM variant emerged as a field modification in 3087, downgrading the turret weaponry to a single Streak SRM-2 while adding a Guardian ECM suite. This configuration proved popular with units operating in electronic warfare environments, where the ECM protection offset the reduced firepower. The full infantry bay was retained, maintaining the Mk II's primary transport mission while adding a valuable force-multiplier capability to the formation.</p>
</history>

